'''Ruth Myers''' (born 1940) is a British costume designer. She has received two [[Academy Award]] nominations as well as two [[BAFTA]] nominations and has won a [[Emmy]] Award for costumes. In 2008 she received the Career Achievement Award at the [[Costume Designers Guild Awards]].

==Career==
Ruth Myers grew up in [[Manchester]] and attended the [[St. Martin's School of Art]] in London. Early in her career she sewed sequins for [[Anthony Powell (designer)|Anthony Powell]] while also working as an assistant to Sophie Devine (costume designer for classic English films). Myers then turned to theatre and low-budget films such as the 1967 comedy ''[[Smashing Time]]''. Upon being persuaded by [[Gene Wilder]], Myers moved to the US and worked with him on the films ''[[The World's Greatest Lover]]'', ''[[The Woman in Red (1984 film)|The Woman in Red]]'', and ''[[Haunted Honeymoon]]''.<ref name=costumeguild/>

Myers acted as costume designer for the 2002 film ''[[The Four Feathers (2002 film)|The Four Feathers]]''<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-92133411.html |title=The Four Feathers |work=[[Daily Variety]] |date=11 September 2002 |accessdate=24 September 2014}} {{subscription needed}}</ref> and the 2008 film ''[[City of Ember]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-188062628.html |title=City of Ember |work=[[Daily Variety]] |first=Justin|last=Chang|date=10 October 2008 |accessdate=24 September 2014}} {{subscription needed}}</ref> She worked with [[Kevin Spacey]] in the films ''[[L.A. Confidential (film)|L.A. Confidential]]'' and ''[[Beyond the Sea (film)|Beyond the Sea]]''. For the latter production, she used textiles from the 1950s and 1960s and ultimately designed 65 outfit changes for Spacey that appear in the film. The actor, who portrayed singer [[Bobby Darin]], had to wear a wide range of costumes as a reflection of his life's journey, from bright suits to his signature red sweater.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-127936951.html |title=Beyond the Sea |work=[[Daily Variety]] |first=Sam|last=Molineaux|date=10 January 2005 |accessdate=24 September 2014}} {{subscription needed}}</ref>

In 2008 Myers received the Career Achievement Award at the [[Costume Designers Guild Awards]].<ref name=costumeguild>{{Cite news|url=http://public.costumedesignersguild.com/aw-archive/cat4-2008-myers/ |title=Lacoste Career Achievement in Film Award |publisher=[[Costume Designers Guild]] |accessdate=24 September 2014}}</ref> In 2011 she designed the costumes for the supernatural teen drama film ''[[Vampire Academy (film)|Vampire Academy]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://variety.com/2014/film/reviews/film-review-vampire-academy-1201098296/ |title=Film Review: <U+2018>Vampire Academy<U+2019> |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |first=Dennis |last=Harvey |date=11 February 2014 |accessdate=24 September 2014}}</ref> The following year, Myers oversaw costume design for the television miniseries ''[[Hemingway & Gellhorn]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/fashion/nicole-kidman-has-the-perfect-figure-20120801-23ebq.html |title=Nicole Kidman 'has the perfect figure' |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=1 August 2012 |accessdate=24 September 2014}}</ref> Myers' efforts earned her a nomination in the outstanding made-for-television movie or miniseries category at the [[Costume Designers Guild Awards]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/jan/17/entertainment/la-et-mn-argo-skyfall-receive-costume-designers-guild-nominations-20130116 |title='Argo,' 'Skyfall' among nominees for Costume Designers Guild Awards |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=17 January 2013|first=Susan |last=King |accessdate=24 September 2014}}</ref>

==Award history==
===Oscar nominations===
Both are in the category of [[Academy Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costumes]].

*[[64th Academy Awards]]-Nominated for ''[[The Addams Family (film)|The Adadms Family]]''. Lost to ''[[Bugsy]]''.<ref name="Oscars1992">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/64th-winners.html |title=The 64th Academy Awards (1992) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=30 March 2014|work=''Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences''|publisher=AMPAS}}</ref>
*[[69th Academy Awards]]-Nominated for ''[[Emma (1996 theatrical film)|Emma]]''. Lost to ''[[The English Patient (film)|The English Patient]]''.<ref name="Oscars1997">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/69th-winners.html |title=The 69th Academy Awards (1997) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=30 March 2014|work=oscars.org}}</ref>

===Emmy nominations===
Both are for costumes.

*[[56th Primetime Emmy Awards]]-''[[Carniv<U+00E0>le]]''-'''Won.'''
*[[64th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards]]-Nominated for ''[[Hemingway & Gellhorn]]''. Lost to ''[[Great Expectations (2011 TV serial)|Great Expectations]]''. 

===BAFTA nominations===
Both are for [[BAFTA Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design]].

*[[23rd British Academy Film Awards]]-Nominated for ''[[Isadora]]''. Lost to ''[[Oh! What a Lovely War]]''.
*[[51st British Academy Film Awards]]-Nominated for ''[[L.A. Confidential (film)|L.A. Confidential]]''. Lost to ''[[Mrs. Brown (film)|Mrs. Brown]]''.

